=============================================
Dugga 5 – Question
Euler path in the given graph
Nodes between which an Euler trail exists
=============================================

We want:
1) The two endpoints of an Euler path.
2) One explicit Euler path found with the systematic method.

---------------------------------------------
PART (1) — Degrees and endpoints
---------------------------------------------
I list all nodes and count degrees (number of edges incident to each):

deg(1)  = 2   (1–2, 1–3)
deg(2)  = 4   (2–1, 2–3, 2–5, 2–6)
deg(3)  = 4   (3–1, 3–2, 3–4, 3–5)
deg(4)  = 2   (4–3, 4–9)
deg(5)  = 4   (5–2, 5–3, 5–7, 5–8)
deg(6)  = 3   (6–2, 6–7, 6–11)
deg(7)  = 4   (7–5, 7–6, 7–8, 7–10)
deg(8)  = 4   (8–5, 8–7, 8–9, 8–10)
deg(9)  = 3   (9–4, 9–8, 9–13)
deg(10) = 4   (10–7, 10–8, 10–11, 10–12)
deg(11) = 4   (11–6, 11–10, 11–12, 11–14)
deg(12) = 4   (12–10, 12–11, 12–13, 12–14)
deg(13) = 2   (13–9, 13–12)
deg(14) = 2   (14–11, 14–12)

Only nodes 6 and 9 have odd degree (3 each).

Euler-path criterion:
- A connected graph has an Euler path if exactly two vertices have odd degree.
- Those two are the start and end.

So the Euler path goes between nodes 6 and 9.

Answer:
[6, 9]

---------------------------------------------
PART (2) — Systematic construction of an Euler path
---------------------------------------------
Now I actually build one Euler path using the standard “cycle + insertion” method.

Step 1 – First cycle starting at 6  
I walk from 6, always taking an unused edge, until I get back to 6:

6 → 7 → 10 → 12 → 14 → 11 → 10 → 8 → 9 → 13 → 12 → 11 → 6

This is a closed trail (a cycle) that uses a bunch of edges.

Step 2 – Remaining edges and new trail from 6  
Some edges incident with 6 (and other nodes) are still unused.  
From 6 I build another trail using only unused edges:

6 → 2 → 5 → 8 → 7 → 5 → 3 → 2 → 1 → 3 → 4 → 9

This starts at 6 and ends at 9, and uses all edges that were left.

Step 3 – Splice the trails to get one Euler path  
I insert the second trail into the first at node 6 (where they meet).  
The combined Euler path is:

6 → 7 → 10 → 12 → 14 → 11 → 10 → 8 → 9 → 13 → 12 → 11 → 6  
→ 2 → 5 → 8 → 7 → 5 → 3 → 2 → 1 → 3 → 4 → 9

Or in one line:

Euler path:
6–7–10–12–14–11–10–8–9–13–12–11–6–2–5–8–7–5–3–2–1–3–4–9

This starts at 6, ends at 9, and uses every edge exactly once,  
so it is a valid Eulerväg constructed with the systematic method.